comment: Vol. T1: 200 µL (layer 1). Upon start of printing, printer starts with rotation to vat 2. As the printhead was manually lowered to Z = 30, crashing was imminent and an emergency power kill was performed to avoid that. Moreover, driving of printhead into FEP film/underlying acrylic glass window (ca. 0.5 mm) leads to bending -> first layers might not be printed due to effective homing to Z < 0 -> setting global offset to compensate.
next steps: Recycling of pipetted T1. Restart/reinitiation of printer. Setting global offset to 0.5.

comment: Vol. T1: 200 µL (layer 1). Vol. T2: 100 µL (layer 2). HAMA ink (T2) very motile on FEP film -> not centred when printhead is lowered -> only ca. half of base GelMA layer covered with T2. Moreover, strange defect: construct significantly thicker on the side where T2 was. Looks like not just channels were printed but also in between -> overcuring? However, offset seems to be wrong as HAMA layer looks thicker than 200 µm.
next steps: Recycling of T1/T2. Increase T1 exp. 20 -> 30 sec. Increase T2 vol. 100 -> 200 µL and try to pipet it more to the centre of the projection.

comment: Vol. T1: +100 µL (layer 1). Vol. T2: 200 µL (layer 2). T2 completely covering GelMA base due to higher vol. and more centred positioning. But still overall HAMA layer height seem to be too big and channels clearly fused -> wavy surface. S3 not complete on one small side (very minor) due to insufficient coverage with T1. Sample stored in DPBS for later analysis (see lab book AT).
next steps: Break: shut down printer completely. Restart/reinitiation of printer. Decrease T2 exp. 45 -> 30 sec.

comment: Vol. T1: 200 µL (layer 1). Vol. T2: 200 µL (layer 2). T2 drop not centred when printhead is lowered -> ca. 10% of one short site of base GelMA layer not covered with T2. GelMA drop in last layer also slightly misaligned -> two corners of construct with missing material. Sample stored in DPBS for later analysis (see lab book AT).
next steps: Recycling of T1/T2. Decrease T2 exp. 30 -> 20 sec. Increase Z speed 100 -> 150.

comment: Vol. T1: +100 µL (layer 1), +100 µL (layer 3). Vol. T2: 200 µL (layer 2). T2 drop not centred when printhead is lowered -> ca. 10% of one short site of base GelMA layer not covered with T2. GelMA drop in last layer also slightly misaligned -> two corners of construct with missing material. Sample stored in DPBS for later analysis (see lab book AT).
next steps: Leave out T1 and only print channels (layer 2) with HAMA to titrate minimum exposure time/see if defined channel printing is possible. To compensate missing layer 1, offset is changed to 0.2. Decrease T2 exp. 20 -> 15 sec.

comment: Vol. T2: 200 µL (layer 2). Optically, channels are interconnected at base -> create wavy surface. However, upon inspection with plastic spatula, channels are separated as "noodles" and swim separately in petri dish with DPBS -> most likely not welded together during printing but stuck together due to softness, fragility and proximity to each other.
next steps: Go back to full construct printing. Offset changed back to 0.5. Try printing 4x constructs in parallel.

comment: Vol. T1: 800 µL (layer 1), +400 µL (layer 3). Vol. T2: 500 µL (layer 2). All vol. provide good coverage of all constructs. All constructs printed successfully. Seem to be slightly connected/no sharp edges of GelMA -> softness/overcuring? Removal with spatula difficult/produces abrasions on lower surface. Samples stored in DPBS for later analysis (see lab book AT).
